    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-11T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-11T09:00:00-05:00" n="115"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d115">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8703: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-11T22:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 11, 1937—[10 p.m.]</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 11—11:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>219. Embassy’s 217, July 11, 3 p.m.<note n="59" xml:id="d115fn59">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Reuter publishes late this afternoon despatch under Tientsin date line
                        that “Japanese military headquarters at Tientsin state that the total
                        Japanese casualties in the Wanping area since fighting began on
                            Wednesday–Thursday<note n="60" xml:id="d115fn60">July 7–8.</note> night
                        are 18 killed and 40 wounded”.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The same release states that “four demands are being presented to the
                        Chinese authorities by the Japanese in consequence of the incidents in the
                        Wanping area. They are: (1) the withdrawal of Chinese troops from the
                        vicinity of Marco Polo Bridge; (2) punishment of those responsible for the
                        incidents; (3) adequate control of anti-Japanese activities in North China;
                        (4) enforcement of anti-Communist measures.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>An official of the local Japanese Embassy stated to this Embassy that he
                        believes an agreement is near.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
